WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:10.160
<v Teacher>So, we have seen how we can use the present to talk about the future in Spanish using <b>voy a</b>, <b>vamos </b> <b>a</b>, or using some future context

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:15.740
<v Teacher>(<b>pronto</b>- <i>soon</i>, <b>mañana</b>- <i>tomorrow</i>, <b>la semana que viene</b>- <i>the </i> <i>week that comes</i>- <i>next week</i>).

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:19.660
<v Teacher>But we can also use the present in Spanish to talk about the past,

00:00:19.539 --> 00:00:21.539
<v Teacher>just as we can in English.

00:00:21.539 --> 00:00:28.099
<v Teacher>In English and in Spanish we have three ways to talk about the past, or three main ways to talk about the past.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.600
<v Teacher>We can say, for example: <i>I ate</i>.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.480
<v Teacher>We can say: <i>I was eating</i>.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.320
<v Teacher>And we can say: <i>I have eaten</i>.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.360
<v Teacher>Now, when we say <i>I have eaten</i>, we are using <i>I have</i>, which is the present,

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:48.320
<v Teacher>and then <i>eaten</i> is like a version of the verb which is kind of complicated in English.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.960
<v Teacher>You say <i>I have eaten</i>, <i>I have gone</i>, <i>I </i> <i>have wanted</i>.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.920
<v Teacher><i>Wanted, eaten, gone, </i>they are all very different.

00:00:55.920 --> 00:00:58.720
<v Teacher>So that is kind of complicated in English, how to build that.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.280
<v Teacher>But in Spanish it is very simple.

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:05.479
<v Teacher>So, we have: <i>I ate, I was eating</i>, and <i>I have eaten</i>.

00:01:05.479 --> 00:01:10.040
<v Teacher>This <i>I have eaten</i> is going to be the first past that we learn.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.280
<v Teacher>And we are actually using the present.

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:13.119
<v Teacher>Now, this <i>have</i> is not <b>tener</b>.

00:01:13.119 --> 00:01:19.360
<v Teacher><b>Tener</b> we use for possession, and we use with the combination of <b>que</b> to give this meaning of "have to".

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:27.820
<v Teacher>Now, the verb that we use for <i>have</i> in the sense of <i>I have eaten</i>, <i>I have gone</i>, in Spanish it's <b>haber</b>.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:34.600
<v Teacher><b>Haber</b>: <i>h-a-b-e-r</i>. And of course we have the silent <i>h</i> there, in <b>haber</b>.

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:39.640
<v Teacher><b>Haber</b> is <i>to have </i>in the sense of <i>I have eaten</i>. But <b>haber</b> is extremely irregular,

00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:41.020
<v Teacher>there is no “habo”,

00:01:41.020 --> 00:01:42.780
<v Teacher>it is extremely irregular.

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:48.380
<v Teacher>But there is a very easy way we can remember all of the versions of <b>haber</b>, even though it is very irregular.

00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:53.979
<v Teacher>What are the two vowel sounds that we have inside of the verb <b>haber</b>?

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:55.580
<v Student>/<i>a</i>/ and /<i>e</i>/.

00:01:55.580 --> 00:01:55.980
<v Teacher>Good,

00:01:55.980 --> 00:02:02.060
<v Teacher>we have /<i>a</i>/ and /<i>e</i>/ inside the word <b>haber</b>, and we are going to use that to help us remember the versions.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:03.580
<v Teacher>Let's start with <b>he</b>.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:07.560
<v Student><b>He</b>. All by itself, it means <i>I have</i>.

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:09.640
<v Teacher>It is spelled <i>h-e</i>.

00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:15.320
<v Teacher>And of course, we have the silent <i>h</i> there from <b>haber</b> in <b>he</b> (<i>h-e</i>).

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:16.200
<v Teacher><i>I have</i>.

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:22.980
<v Teacher>We actually saw already one other verb that forms its <i>I</i> version in this way.

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:24.660
<v Teacher>What was <i>to know</i>?

00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:26.500
<v Student><b>Saber</b>.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:27.380
<v Teacher><b>Saber</b>.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:28.820
<v Teacher>And <i>I know</i> is?

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:31.980
<v Student><b>Sé</b>.

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:35.020
<v Teacher><i>I have</i> from <b>haber</b> is spelled <i>h-e</i>,

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:37.580
<v Teacher>just like <b>sé</b> from <b>saber</b> is spelled <i>s-e</i>.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:43.660
<v Teacher>They are the only two verbs that form the <i>I</i> version in this way, in this very irregular way.

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:48.800
<v Teacher>So you get <b>sé</b> from <b>saber</b>, and you get <b>he</b> from <b>haber</b>.

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:53.440
<v Teacher>Different from <b>saber</b>, all of the versions of <b>haber</b> are irregular.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:58.000
<v Teacher>Now, <i>I</i> and <i>we</i> are connected.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.519
<v Teacher>We can see how <i>we</i> is the plural of <i>I</i>.

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:06.800
<v Teacher><i>I</i>, and then when I include <i>you</i> and I say <i>we</i>, it is like the plural of <i>I</i>.

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:08.959
<v Teacher>So, <i>I</i> and <i>we</i> are connected.

00:03:08.959 --> 00:03:13.120
<v Teacher>So, just knowing that, if you had to guess what is <i>we have,</i>

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:16.220
<v Teacher>knowing that <i>I have </i>is <b>he</b>,

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:18.140
<v Teacher>what do you think you would guess?

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:19.180
<v Student>Hes?

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:22.380
<v Teacher>This works with nouns and adjectives.

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:31.920
<v Teacher>So, it is a very good example of why, whilst we are avoiding grammatical terminology, we want to know what type of word we are dealing with, because different words behave in different ways.

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:44.500
<v Teacher>Nouns, words you can put <i>the</i> or <i>a</i> in front of: <b>la semana, </b> <b>una semana</b>- <i>the week, a week; </i>and adjectives, words that describe, that you can put <i>is</i> in front of: <i>is red</i>, <i>is tall</i>:

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:50.240
<v Teacher>these words use -<i>s</i> for plural. But we have never seen the verb do that, have we?

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:52.720
<v Teacher>What does the verb use for <i>we</i>?

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:53.800
<v Student>-<b>amos</b>.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:54.600
<v Teacher>Or?

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:55.240
<v Student>-<b>emos</b>.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:55.480
<v Teacher>Or?

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:56.120
<v Student>-<b>imos</b>.

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:57.320
<v Teacher>And what do they have in common,

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:58.680
<v Teacher>-<i>amos, -emos, -imos</i>?

00:03:59.000 --> 00:03:59.640
<v Student>The -<i>mos</i>.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:00.280
<v Teacher>Good,

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:01.240
<v Teacher>ok.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:06.220
<v Teacher>So if <b>he</b> is <i>I have</i> (<i>h-e</i>), how do you think it might be <i>we have</i>?

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:06.860
<v Student><b>Hemos</b>.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:07.660
<v Teacher><b>Hemos</b>.

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:08.140
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:10.700
<v Teacher>So, from <b>haber</b> you get <b>he</b> and <b>hemos</b>,

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:11.960
<v Teacher>no?

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.400
<v Teacher>And we don't want to memorise this,

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:15.160
<v Teacher>we said we can think just this thought,

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:15.960
<v Teacher>just the thought

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:17.959
<v Teacher>"What vowels do we have in <b>haber</b>?

00:04:17.959 --> 00:04:18.760
<v Teacher>/<i>a</i>/ and /<i>e</i>/.

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:19.480
<v Teacher>Ok: <b>he</b>.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:24.480
<v Teacher><b>He</b> by itself is <i>I</i>, it is connected to <i>we:</i> <b>he</b> and <b>hemos</b>."

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.320
<v Teacher>Now we go to the other vowel

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:27.120
<v Teacher>/<i>a</i>/.

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:28.080
<v Teacher><i>H-a</i>

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:29.280
<v Teacher>all by itself

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:31.440
<v Teacher><b>ha</b> means

00:04:31.639 --> 00:04:36.040
<v Teacher><i>she has, it has, he has, you</i> (formal) <i>have</i>.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:38.199
<v Teacher>Now I am sure you can tell me the rest of them.

00:04:38.199 --> 00:04:39.400
<v Teacher>What are the other versions?

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:41.160
<v Teacher>What is <i>they have</i>?

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:41.960
<v Student><b>Han</b>.

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:42.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:42.520 --> 00:04:50.680
<v Teacher>So, we start with this base of <b>he</b> and <b>ha</b>, and we can remember that just by looking at the vowels that are inside <b>haber</b>. And then, we can add on what we need.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:58.500
<v Teacher>So, we have <b>he</b> for <i>I have</i>, <b>hemos</b> for <i>we have</i>, we have <b>ha</b> (<i>h-a</i>) for <i>he/she/it/you </i>(formal) <i>have</i> or <i>has</i>,

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:00.900
<v Teacher>you added an -<i>n</i> and what did you get?

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:01.740
<v Student><b>Han</b>.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:03.340
<v Teacher>And what does that mean?

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:04.940
<v Student><i>They have</i>.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:06.140
<v Teacher>Or?

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:07.420
<v Student><i>You guys have</i>.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:07.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:11.580
<v Teacher>And how would you say <i>you have</i> informally?

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:13.139
<v Student><b>Has</b>.

00:05:13.139 --> 00:05:13.780
<v Teacher><b>Has</b>.

00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:14.099
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:14.099 --> 00:05:15.300
<v Teacher>And that is your set:

00:05:15.699 --> 00:05:17.699
<v Teacher><b>he-hemos, ha-has-han</b>.

00:05:17.699 --> 00:05:20.580
<v Teacher>So you have two key vowel sounds /e/ and /a/.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:25.500
<v Teacher><b>He-hemos </b>for <i>I</i> and for <i>we</i> (for <i>I</i> and the plural of <i>I</i> which is <i>we</i>).

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:32.379
<v Teacher>And then you have <b>ha</b> for <i>he-she-it</i>, <b>han</b> for <i>they</i>, <b>has</b> for <i>you</i> (informal).

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:37.780
<v Teacher>Now we need to learn how to make <i>eaten</i>, how to make <i>gone</i>, how to make <i>wanted</i>,

00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:42.180
<v Teacher>if we want to say <i>I have eaten</i>, <i>I have gone</i>, <i>I have wanted</i>.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.340
<v Teacher>This is very simple in Spanish.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:51.920
<v Teacher>-<i>ar</i> verbs will lose their -<i>ar</i>, they will lose their final -<i>ar</i>, and they will put -<i>ado</i> on the end.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:56.000
<v Teacher>So for example, we have <i>to speak</i> which is <b>hablar</b>.

00:05:55.840 --> 00:06:02.240
<v Teacher>If you want to build <i>spoken</i>, you take off that -<i>ar</i> and you put on -<i>ado</i>.

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:03.200
<v Student><b>Hablado</b>.

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:06.080
<v Teacher>Now we can speak about the past.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:08.720
<v Teacher>Now we can say <i>I have spoken</i>,

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:10.980
<v Teacher>and we need to think about the two bits separately.

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:13.380
<v Teacher><i>I have spoken</i>:

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:15.700
<v Student>Is it <b>he</b>? <b>He hablado</b>.

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:16.180
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:17.460
<v Teacher><b>He hablado</b>.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:18.820
<v Teacher><i>I haven't spoken.</i>

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.660
<v Teacher>Where do you think the <i>no</i> is going

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.220
<v Teacher><i>I haven't </i> <i>spoken:</i>

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:23.819
<v Student>In the beginning.

00:06:23.819 --> 00:06:25.340
<v Student><b>No he hablado</b>.

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:26.060
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:27.659
<v Teacher><b>No he hablado</b>.

00:06:27.659 --> 00:06:28.620
<v Teacher><i>I haven't spoken</i>.

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:30.620
<v Teacher><i>We have spoken</i>?

00:06:30.620 --> 00:06:33.259
<v Student><b>Hemos hablado</b>.

00:06:33.259 --> 00:06:34.940
<v Teacher><b>Hemos hablado</b>. <i>He has spoken</i>:

00:06:35.599 --> 00:06:37.199
<v Student><b>Ha hablado</b>.

00:06:37.199 --> 00:06:37.759
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:37.759 --> 00:06:39.840
<v Teacher><i>She has spoken</i>?

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:41.120
<v Student><b>Ha hablado</b>.

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:41.599
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:41.599 --> 00:06:43.120
<v Teacher><i>They</i>?

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:44.479
<v Student><b>Han hablado</b>.

00:06:44.479 --> 00:06:45.440
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal)?

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:48.300
<v Student><b>Has hablado</b>.

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:48.860
<v Teacher>Perfect,

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:50.220
<v Teacher>well done.

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:57.020
<v Teacher>Now, this is actually more useful, this past, than what you might think it is, because this is used

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:01.200
<v Teacher>even more in Spanish than it is in English.

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:03.920
<v Teacher>So maybe you want the past <i>I spoke</i>,

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:06.960
<v Teacher>but you can use, for now, <i>I have spoken</i>.

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:10.320
<v Teacher>This "have past" is very popular

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:13.280
<v Teacher>and used much more than in English.

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:16.720
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>anticipation</i>?

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:18.480
<v Student><b>Anticipación</b>.

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:18.800
<v Teacher>Good,

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:20.160
<v Teacher>and <i>to anticipate</i>?

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:22.240
<v Student><b>Anticipar</b>.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:22.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:26.560
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>we have anticipated it</i>?

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:28.880
<v Teacher>So, there is a few things you have to think about.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:31.759
<v Teacher>Think about them separately, then put them together.

00:07:31.759 --> 00:07:35.199
<v Teacher><i>We have anticipated it.</i>

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:45.620
<v Teacher>So, to get <i>anticipated</i> you take away the -<i>ar</i>, and you put -<i>ado</i>.

00:07:45.620 --> 00:07:46.180
<v Student>Ah! Yes.

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:50.520
<v Student><b>Hemos anticipado lo</b>.

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:53.520
<v Teacher>And where does that <b>lo</b> go? Because <b>anticipado</b> is not like-

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:55.520
<v Student>Ah! It has changed now, so it is in the beginning.

00:07:55.520 --> 00:07:55.919
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:07:55.919 --> 00:07:56.800
<v Student>So, lo

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:59.100
<v Student>hemos anticipado.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:07:59.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:02.060
<v Teacher><b>Lo hemos anticipado</b>.

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:09.660
<v Teacher>The word for <i>for</i>, like in time, <i>we have anticipated it for a long time</i> for example, is <b>por</b>.

00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:10.140
<v Teacher><b>Por</b>.

00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:11.940
<v Student><b>Por</b>.

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:16.940
<v Teacher>You might know <b>por favor</b>, which means <i>please</i> in Spanish. Which means "for a favour".

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:18.860
<v Teacher><b>Por</b> <b>favor</b>, "for a favour".

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:23.980
<v Teacher>So this <b>por</b> is also <i>for</i>, in the sense of "for periods of time."

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:33.560
<v Teacher>So, if you want to <i>say we have anticipated it for a long time</i>, we will just say <i>we have anticipated it for much time</i>.

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:38.360
<v Teacher>maybe there are some bits in there that you think you don't know. But we will see when we get to them.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:41.080
<v Teacher>So, the first bit is <i>we have anticipated it</i>.

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:43.320
<v Student><b>Lo hemos anticipado</b>.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:43.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:46.840
<v Teacher><i>For</i>: <b>Por</b>. <i>A lot </i>or<i> much</i>:

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:48.800
<v Student><b>Mucho</b>.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:49.680
<v Teacher><i>Time</i>.

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:55.520
<v Teacher>We saw briefly before that we have a word in English that we use for <i>time</i>, that we only use with music.

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:56.720
<v Teacher>What was that word?

00:08:56.720 --> 00:08:57.440
<v Student><i>Tempo</i>.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:08:58.080
<v Teacher><i>Tempo</i>.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.320
<v Teacher>And how did it change in Spanish?

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:01.360
<v Student><b>Tiempo</b>?

00:09:01.360 --> 00:09:03.200
<v Teacher><b>Tiempo</b>, yes! The <i>e</i> split.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:07.600
<v Teacher>So: <i>we have anticipated it for a long time</i>.

00:09:12.339 --> 00:09:13.139
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:13.139 --> 00:09:16.740
<v Teacher><b>Lo hemos anticipado por mucho tiempo</b>.

00:09:16.740 --> 00:09:17.540
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:20.819
<v Teacher>Maybe you want to ask somebody <i>Did you celebrate?</i>

00:09:20.459 --> 00:09:23.580
<v Teacher>And you think "oh, I don't know <i>did</i> yet in Spanish".

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:25.420
<v Teacher>You can just say: <i>Have </i> <i>you celebrated</i>?

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:26.380
<v Teacher>And that is fine.

00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:30.940
<v Teacher>Like I said, it is used even more in Spanish than in English.

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:35.959
<v Teacher>So, some certain situations it might sound a little bit uncomfortable the translation into English.

00:09:35.959 --> 00:09:38.440
<v Teacher>But in Spanish, most of the time, it is going to be fine.

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:40.199
<v Teacher>So, <i>have you celebrated</i>?

00:09:40.199 --> 00:09:42.519
<v Teacher>Let’s speak informally.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:48.200
<v Student><b>Has – celebración... celebrar... celebrado.</b>

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:49.080
<v Teacher>Good,

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:49.640
<v Teacher>good.

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:51.720
<v Student>So, ¿<b>has celebrado?</b>

00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:52.280
<v Teacher>Good,

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:53.880
<v Teacher>¿<b>has celebrado</b>?

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:56.040
<v Teacher><i>Haven't you celebrated</i>?

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:58.480
<v Student>¿<b>No has celebrado</b>?

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:00.880
<v Teacher><i>Why haven't you celebrated</i>?

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:03.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:05.440
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>where</i>?

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:07.360
<v Student><b>Dónde.</b>

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:09.520
<v Teacher><i>Where have you celebrated</i>?

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:13.180
<v Student>¿<b>Dónde has celebrado</b>?

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:13.820
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:16.940
<v Teacher><i>Where have you celebrated it?</i>

00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:19.420
<v Student>¿<b>Dónde lo has celebrado</b>?

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:19.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:31.280
<v Teacher>So, -<i>ar</i> verbs, we take away the -<i>ar</i> and we put -<i>ado</i>. And we get this version of the verb that we need after <b>haber</b>, which in English has many different forms.

00:10:31.060 --> 00:10:35.060
<v Teacher>Like I said: <i>you have gone, </i> <i>wanted, eaten...</i> it changes a lot.

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:39.140
<v Teacher>But in Spanish we get rid of the -<i>ar</i> and we put -<i>ado</i>.

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:40.660
<v Teacher>We said that <i>to take</i>,

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:43.860
<v Teacher>and also sometimes <i>to drink</i>, is <b>tomar</b>.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:44.900
<v Teacher><b>Tomar</b>.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:45.860
<v Student><b>Tomar</b>.

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:49.460
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I have taken</i>?

00:10:50.360 --> 00:10:51.960
<v Student><b>He tomado</b>.

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:53.880
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.200
<v Teacher><i>We have taken</i>:

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:58.440
<v Student><b>Hemos tomado</b>.

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.600
<v Teacher>Good. <i>Has she taken it? Has she taken it?</i>

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:03.240
<v Teacher><i>Has she taken it?</i>

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:06.340
<v Student>¿<b>Han lo tomado</b>?

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:07.460
<v Teacher>That is a guess,

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:09.780
<v Teacher>you are looking at me like it is a guess

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:15.140
<v Teacher>I want you to establish your own thought process of how you are going to find it.

00:11:14.759 --> 00:11:17.079
<v Teacher>So what is the first bit you need to think about?

00:11:17.079 --> 00:11:19.480
<v Teacher><i>Has she </i> <i>taken it?</i>

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:20.839
<v Student><i>Has she</i>.

00:11:20.839 --> 00:11:21.399
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:21.399 --> 00:11:22.759
<v Teacher>What is that?

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:26.399
<v Student>Ok, so it is <b>he</b> and <b>hemos</b> for <i>I</i> and <i>we</i>.

00:11:26.399 --> 00:11:26.800
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:33.600
<v Student>So it is.. oh! It is <b>ha</b>! It is just <b>ha</b>. Yes. So, <i>has she taken it?</i>

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:36.259
<v Student>¿<b>Lo ha tomado</b>?

00:11:36.899 --> 00:11:39.459
<v Teacher>Sometimes I am going to build you up step by step,

00:11:39.459 --> 00:11:46.259
<v Teacher>sometimes I am just going to give you the sentence and you need to deconstruct what thoughts you need to have first,

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:53.620
<v Teacher>and to divide it up into various thoughts to get the sentence, resisting any temptation to guess or to say something that we are not sure of.

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:54.900
<v Teacher>You can be sure and be wrong,

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:56.340
<v Teacher>there is no problem there,

00:11:56.519 --> 00:12:01.800
<v Teacher>But we want to think about it, dividing the sentence up into each individual thing we need to think about.

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:02.920
<v Teacher>First, <i>she has</i>, <b>ha</b>.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:04.920
<v Teacher><i>She has taken</i>, <b>ha tomado</b>.

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:06.940
<v Teacher><i>She has taken it</i>.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:07.820
<v Teacher><i>It</i> is <b>lo</b>,

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:10.700
<v Teacher>where do I put the <b>lo</b>? Before the changed verb.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:11.900
<v Teacher><b>Lo ha tomado</b>.
